The design and fabrication strategy of different paper electrodes is represented in Fig. 1. Common paper is composed of polymeric cellulose strands which have abundant –OH functional groups on the surface that facilitate the strong anchoring of different precursors that are used during electroless plating of metallic Ni0. Electroless plating is a well-established process which involves reduction of metal ions from an aqueous bath with a reducing agent (e.g., NaH2PO2) and a catalyst (e.g., Pd0)25–28. While the reducing agent is simply dissolved in the plating bath, the catalyst is deposited onto the substrate to be coated through a redox reaction involving Sn2+ ions. This two-step process is summarized in the Eqs. 1 and 2:1Sn2++Pd2+→Sn4++Pd0,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
